Natural-language product-level rule:
${naturalLanguage}

Context:
${contextSummary}

Identified target category codes:
${targetCategories}

Product context JSON:
${contextJson}

SDK profile:
${sdkProfile}

Allowed SDK APIs:
${allowedSdkApis}

Forbidden SDK APIs:
${forbiddenSdkApis}

Generate exactly one Java rule method body for a ModuleAlgBase subclass rule method.
Requirements:
- Return only Java statements for the method body.
- Do not include package, imports, class declarations, annotations, method declarations,
  markdown, or explanations.
- @CodeRuleAnno, method name, method header, and rule identifier are generated by RuleTrans templates.
- If an API requires a rule code, use the existing local variable named ruleCode.
- For cross-category incompatibility, prefer inCompatible(ruleCode, "category:Attr=value",
  "category:Attr=value") when it expresses the business rule.
- inCompatible accepts exactly three arguments: ruleCode variable, left expression string, right expression string.
  Do not pass partVar(...), PartVar, lists, or ParaVar values to inCompatible.
- For parameter compatibility rules, use addCompatibleConstraintRequires(ruleCode, leftPara,
  listOf("leftOption"), rightPara, listOf("rightOption")), addCompatibleConstraintInCompatible(...),
  or addCompatibleConstraintCoDependent(...).
- Otherwise use model().sum4Selected(...), model().sum4Quantity(...), and other southbound facade APIs.
- For aggregate quantity or weighted dynamic-attribute totals, prefer
  model().sum4Quantity("categoryCodeOrCommaSeparatedCodes", "attrCodeOrBlank", "optional Attr=value filter").
- The attrCode argument is a numeric weighting attribute, not a filter attribute. For selected-count rules
  such as at most/exactly/at least N selected parts, use attrCode "" and put attribute predicates in
  the filter condition. For total part quantity rules, also use attrCode "" unless the rule says weighted
  by a numeric dynamic attribute.
- For cross-category aggregate totals, use comma-separated category codes in the first argument.
- For aggregate totals over all instances of a multi-instance category, suffix that category code with * in
  the first argument.
- For supportMultiInst categories, plain categoryCode means one/current instance only; when the rule says
  all instances, every instance, all-instance aggregate, 全部实例, 所有实例, or 全实例汇总, the first argument
  must use categoryCode*. This also applies to phrases like all <categoryCode> instances or 所有 <categoryCode> 实例.
- Do not add * only because a category supports multi-instance; use * only when the natural language explicitly
  asks for all instances of that category.
- Do not mix * and comma-separated categories in one aggregate call, such as "disk*,mainBoard".
  If a true rule needs all instances of one category plus another category, build separate aggregate
  expressions and combine them with model().newPartLinearExpr(...).addExpr(...).
- Do not enumerate atomic parts with partVar(...).quantityVar() to build aggregate or weighted totals.
- In filter conditions, use dynamic attribute values from context dynAttr or option codeValue, not option codes.
- Filter conditions are rule-engine strings such as Attr=value or Attr>=number; do not use Java == and do
  not quote string values inside the filter.
- For numeric constraints, use model().addLessOrEqual(...), model().addGreaterOrEqual(...),
  or model().addEquality(...).
- For direct parameter/part expressions, use existing Java fields by code or accessors by code, such as
  para("p1").valueVar(), para("p1").option("optionCode").selectedVar(),
  partVar("part1").quantityVar(), and partVar("part1").hiddenVar().
- For linear expressions, AlgCPLinearExpr.addTerm and PartAlgCPLinearExpr.addTerm use
  addTerm(variable, coefficient), such as expr.addTerm(para("p1").valueVar(), 1).
  Do not reverse the arguments.
- To combine aggregate PartAlgCPLinearExpr values such as model().sum4Quantity(...) or
  model().sum4Selected(...), use objectiveExpr.addExpr(aggregateExpr, coefficient).
  Do not pass aggregate expressions to addTerm(...).
- PartAlgCPLinearExpr is also a linear expression. It can be used in numeric constraints such as
  model().addGreaterOrEqual(totalExpr, 0), model().addLessOrEqual(totalExpr, limit), or
  model().addGreaterOrEqual(totalExpr, para("p1").valueVar()). When comparing an aggregate expression
  with a parameter, use para("p1").valueVar(), not the ParaVar itself.
- For boolean conditions, use AlgCPBoolVar with model().newBoolVar(...), model().addBoolAnd(...),
  model().addBoolOr(...), and onlyEnforceIf(...).
- model().addBoolAnd and model().addBoolOr accept exactly one AlgCPLiteral[] argument.
  Do not call model().addBoolAnd(conditionVar, a, b) or model().addBoolOr(conditionVar, a, b).
- To define cond = a AND b, use model().addBoolAnd(new AlgCPLiteral[] {a, b}).onlyEnforceIf(cond)
  and model().addBoolOr(new AlgCPLiteral[] {a.not(), b.not()}).onlyEnforceIf(cond.not()).
- To define cond = a OR b, use model().addBoolOr(new AlgCPLiteral[] {a, b}).onlyEnforceIf(cond)
  and model().addBoolAnd(new AlgCPLiteral[] {a.not(), b.not()}).onlyEnforceIf(cond.not()).
- model().addEquality(...), model().addDifferent(...), model().addLessOrEqual(...),
  model().addGreaterOrEqual(...), and similar numeric APIs return AlgCPConstraint, not AlgCPLiteral.
  Never put those calls inside AlgCPLiteral[] and never pass them to model().addImplication(...).
- To use a numeric predicate as a boolean literal, first create an AlgCPBoolVar and bind both directions:
  model().addEquality(expr, value).onlyEnforceIf(eqVar);
  model().addDifferent(expr, value).onlyEnforceIf(eqVar.not());
- model().addImplication(left, right) accepts AlgCPLiteral arguments only, such as BoolVar,
  hiddenVar(), option(...).selectedVar(), or their .not() forms.
- For hidden rules, use addVarAboutHiddenConstraints(para("p1"), para("p2")) for hidden ParaVar values
  or addVarAboutHiddenConstraints(partVar("part1"), partVar("part2")) for hidden PartVar values.
  addVarAboutHiddenConstraints is a direct ModuleAlgBase method, not a model() method. Do not pass
  ruleCode, hiddenVar(), valueVar(), or BoolVar to it.
- If a rule can hide a parameter or part, call addVarAboutHiddenConstraints(...) for every parameter
  or part whose hiddenVar() is controlled by the rule. Without this registration, the engine adds
  default visible constraints and hidden solutions can become impossible.
- For priority objectives, use PartAlgCPLinearExpr from model().newPartLinearExpr(...),
  model().sum4Selected(...), model().sum4Quantity(...), addExpr(...), model().setObjectExpr(...),
  and updatePriorityObjectFuntion(ruleCode, expr). Use addExpr for aggregate expressions.
- For priority constraints, use normal numeric constraints first, then build a separate objective
  PartAlgCPLinearExpr. model().newPartLinearExpr requires a name string.
- Do not call partCategoryVar(...).count(), totalQuantityVariable(), selectedCount(),
  or model().addConstraint(...).
- Do not use POST instance-view APIs such as currentInst(), parameter(...).setValue(...),
  partCategorySum(...), part(...), partCategory(...), or setDynAttr(...).

Valid example:
inCompatible(ruleCode, "cpu:CoreNum=4", "drive:Speed=5400");
